    steps: [
      { instruction: 'Bring coconut milk to a gentle simmer with galangal, lemongrass, and lime leaves.', instructionFirstSteps: 'Pour the coconut milk into a saucepan and add the sliced galangal, bruised lemongrass stalks, and torn kaffir lime leaves. Heat gently until it reaches a gentle simmer — don\'t let it boil hard or the coconut milk will separate. Simmer for 5 minutes to infuse the aromatics into the rich, creamy base.', instructionChefsTable: 'Bring coconut milk to a gentle simmer (do not boil — the emulsion will break). Add galangal, bruised lemongrass, and torn kaffir lime leaves. Infuse for 5 minutes. Unlike tom yum (which is water-based), tom kha uses coconut milk as the base, which requires lower temperatures to maintain the emulsion.', duration: 5 },
      { instruction: 'Add sliced chicken and mushrooms, cook until chicken is done.', instructionFirstSteps: 'Slice the chicken breast thinly — thin slices cook quickly and stay tender in the coconut milk. Add the chicken and mushrooms to the simmering coconut broth. Cook for about 12 minutes until the chicken is cooked through. The coconut milk keeps the chicken incredibly moist and tender.', instructionChefsTable: 'Slice chicken breast across the grain to 5mm thickness for rapid, even cooking. Add with the mushrooms and poach gently for 10-12 minutes. The low temperature and fat content of coconut milk create an ideal poaching medium, yielding supremely tender protein.', duration: 12 },
      { instruction: 'Season with fish sauce and remove from heat.' },
      { instruction: 'Add lime juice and fresh chilies. Serve garnished with cilantro.' },
    ],
    culturalNote: 'Tom Kha Gai showcases the Thai principle of balancing flavors: the richness of coconut, the sour of lime, the salty of fish sauce, and the heat of chili.',
