    title: 'Gulab Jamun',
    image: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1627308595229-7830a5c91f9f?w=600&h=400&fit=crop',
    category: 'dessert',
    prepTime: 20,
    cookTime: 30,
    servings: 20,
    difficulty: 'Medium',
    ingredients: [
      { name: 'Milk powder', amount: '200g', category: 'Dairy' },
      { name: 'All-purpose flour', amount: '50g', category: 'Pantry' },
      { name: 'Ghee', amount: '2 tbsp', category: 'Dairy' },
      { name: 'Milk', amount: '4-5 tbsp', category: 'Dairy' },
      { name: 'Sugar', amount: '400g', category: 'Pantry' },
      { name: 'Cardamom', amount: '4 pods', category: 'Spices' },
      { name: 'Rose water', amount: '1 tbsp', category: 'Pantry' },
    ],
    steps: [
      { instruction: 'Make sugar syrup by boiling sugar, water, cardamom, and rose water. Set aside.', duration: 10 },
      { instruction: 'Mix milk powder, flour, and ghee. Add milk gradually to form a soft dough.' },
      { instruction: 'Roll into smooth, crack-free balls about 1 inch in diameter.', instructionFirstSteps: 'Take small portions of dough and roll between your palms into perfectly smooth balls — about the size of a large marble. The surface must have NO cracks at all! Any crack will cause the ball to break apart during frying. If the dough seems dry, add a few drops of milk. Roll gently — pressing too hard makes them dense.', instructionChefsTable: 'Form uniform 2cm spheres with absolutely no surface fissures. Cracks cause structural failure during frying. The dough should be soft but not sticky; add milk in drops if needed. The balls will expand approximately 50% during frying, so size accordingly.' },
      { instruction: 'Deep fry on very low heat, turning constantly until deep brown.', instructionFirstSteps: 'Heat oil or ghee to a very low temperature — about 130°C (265°F). This is much lower than normal frying! Gently place the balls in and fry on this low heat, turning constantly with a slotted spoon for about 12 minutes until they\'re a deep, even mahogany brown. If the oil is too hot, the outside burns while the inside stays raw. Transfer immediately to the warm syrup and let soak for at least 2 hours.', instructionChefsTable: 'Fry at 130°C/265°F — critically low temperature for even heat penetration. Agitate constantly to prevent flat spots and ensure uniform browning. Fry for 10-12 minutes to deep mahogany. Transfer directly to warm syrup (60°C) for minimum 2-hour soak.', duration: 12 },
      { instruction: 'Soak fried balls in warm syrup for at least 2 hours before serving.' },
    ],
    culturalNote: 'Gulab jamun is India\'s most beloved sweet, essential at every celebration and festival. The name comes from "gulab" (rose) and "jamun" (a berry-sized fruit).',
